Robert Redford, legend of American cinema, dies at 89
description: From 'The Sting' to 'Out of Africa,' the actor and director embodied a certain kind of American cinema, generous and progressive. To encourage independent production, he created the Sundance Institute in 1981. He died on Tuesday, at the age of 89.

headline: Yohann Aucante, researcher: 'If Swedish unions, among the wealthiest, most powerful and most legitimate, cannot make Tesla yield, who can?'
description: In an op-ed for Le Monde, Yohann Aucante reflects on the 600-day strike led by Sweden's IF Metall union against the American automaker. In his view, this exceptionally large-scale labor action exposes some of the paradoxes of the automotive sector's shift to electric vehicles, a transition that sometimes comes at the expense of workers' rights.

headline: The singular Georges de La Tour at the Musée Jacquemart-André
description: Some 30 works attributed to the painter, whose life remains little known, are on display in Paris. In the absence of a clear chronology, the paintings have been categorized by subject − both secular and sacred.

headline: Antarctica's tourism boom accelerates melting of 'white continent'
description: While the number of tourists has skyrocketed over the past decade, the pristine continent, which is attracting growing interest among researchers, is gradually deteriorating.

headline: Francesca Albanese, a critical Western voice on Gaza
description: At a conference at a left-wing festival near Paris, the UN special rapporteur on the occupied Palestinian territories received a standing ovation after denouncing European governments' inaction over Israel's destruction of Gaza. Her stance has drawn accusations of antisemitism and activism from critics.
